<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-10-09T01:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-10-09T01:00:00-05:00" n="94" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d94">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">893.102S/1908: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Shanghai</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-10-09T14:00:00+08:00">October 9, 1939—2
                                        p.m.</date><lb/>[Received October 9—8:20 a.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>902. Reference my 893, October 6, 10 a.m. I have today replied to
                                British Consul General that I have submitted his letter for the
                                consideration of the Commander-in-Chief and conferred with him on
                                the existing situation, and that it is considered inadvisable to
                                adopt the proposed measure at this time.</p>
                            <p>Repeated to Chungking, Peiping, Tokyo.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>